  ('Why Learn to Code?', 'https://picsum.photos/seed/one/900/510', 3,
    '2.5 quintillion bytes of data are produced every day in the world and that number is going to continue to explode with the popularity of IoT (the Internet of Things). This statement doesn’t seem to answer the question, but bare with me as I set up our current scenario so I can better get to the question. The advent of the smartphone has exploded the way we interact with computer programs as well as how we interact with them. Before the smartphone, it wasn’t easy to jump on to a webpage to Google something you had a question about like a phone number, or directions to a place. With their ease of use and continued growth in power and speed, we turning to cell phones more and more. We can do most of our banking (check balance, transfer funds, etc.), deal with prescriptions, keep in touch with old friends, and so much more. The more ubiquitous they become, the more that coding is involved in all of this. Now to get back to that first sentence. Over 90% of the worlds data has been generated in the last two years, leading us to this enormous amount of data created daily. Why does this matter? Programming is all around us, and it is there to make our lives easier. As we become more reliant on it, the people who know something about it have a leg up over all of the others.  Learning to code can help you to better understand the technology you are using so it doesn’t give you that “it’s always changing, and I always feel behind the curve” feeling. Coding can also just be a hobby that allows you to build something dorky or fun like a robot or a website. Coding also can take the place of tedious tasks and take something monotous and automate it for you so you can focus on what you want to do. The issue that many people have is that they don’t think that they have a skill for it, or they don’t plan on making a living off of it so there is no point in investing so much time into it. Both of those don’t have to be a problem. There are plenty of people who code just for fun and only do it in their spare time. There is also plenty of material for people that are just starting out and want to do something small and easy. There are entire sections of stores dedicated to teaching kids to code by doing fun things like making robots or their very own smart speakers. Learning to do these things yourself empowers you to be able to interact with this coded world around us in a different way. You can use your new found skills to make yourself a website for yourself that better showcases you to potential employers. You can create a simple web scraper that finds the best airline prices for you so you don’t have to manually go through mountains of webpages, putting in the same information over and over again and hoping you don’t miss something. You can create your own twitter bot that re-tweets the most popular tweets on topics you choose so that you can hack your way to a bigger following.\nIt also is a killer way to make a living. People that can code are in high demand and make great money. Going back to how much data is created and how with the Internet of Things will create more, the demand is only going to grow. There are a ton of different kinds of jobs out there from web development, to app making, to data science and more.\nSo, how do you get started? It depends on what you want to do. I will start with learning to program for fun and cover what to do if you want to make a profession out of it in a future article. You can start out without even leaving your house. Find a website that teaches code like Codecademy or Coursera. Many of these websites include free classes. Get a book on coding like “Automate the Boring Stuff with Python”. This is a great book that will teach you to code by giving you projects that will give you a sense of accomplishment when you are done and a feeling that you can actually do something with your coding. By a coding kit at target, Googles AIY projects are great and range from $50 to $95. They combine building a computer that does something (like a voice assistant), with light programming.\nLearning to code doesn’t have to be tough or dorky. It can be something easy and fun that helps you accomplish a task in the end.  It can give you a window to a world into how everything around us operates in the digital age. Learning to code let’s you take the reigns in a world where it feels like the people in the tech world are leading where we are going and how we will get there. It allows you to use  these tools anyway that you want and not just the way that you are told you should.'),
